quizzes.textContent:
[h1]Nested if Statements[/h1]

You can also include, or [b]nest[/b], if statements within another if statement.
[b]For example: [/b] [code format="cs" codeId="830"]int mark = 100;

if (mark >= 50) {
  Console.WriteLine("You passed.");
 [b] if (mark == 100) {
    Console.WriteLine("Perfect!");
  }[/b]
}
else {
  Console.WriteLine("You failed.");
}

/*Outputs
You passed.
Perfect!
*/[/code]
You can nest an unlimited number of if-else statements.
[b]For example:[/b] [code format="cs" codeId="831"]int age = 18;
if (age > 14) {
  if(age > 18) {
    Console.WriteLine("Adult");
  }
  else {
    Console.WriteLine("Teenager");
  }
}
else {
  if (age > 0) {
    Console.WriteLine("Child");
  }
  else {
    Console.WriteLine("Something's wrong");
  }
}
//Outputs "Teenager"[/code]
[note]Remember that all [b]else [/b]clauses must have corresponding [b]if [/b]statements.[/note]

[h1]The if-else if Statement[/h1]

The[b] if-else if[/b] statement can be used to decide among three or more actions.
[b]For example: [/b][code format="cs" codeId="832"]int x = 33;

[b]if [/b](x == 8) {
   Console.WriteLine("Value of x is 8");
}
[b]else if[/b] (x == 18) {
   Console.WriteLine("Value of x is 18");
}
[b]else if[/b] (x == 33) {
   Console.WriteLine("Value of x is 33");
}
[b]else [/b]{
   Console.WriteLine("No match");
}
//Outputs "Value of x is 33"[/code]
[note]Remember, that an[b] if[/b] can have zero or more [b]else if[/b]'s and they must come before the last [b]else[/b], which is optional.
Once an [b]else if [/b]succeeds, none of the remaining [b]else if[/b]'s or [b]else [/b]clause will be tested.[/note]
